            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Todd Anderson\u2019s hands, calloused from decades of handling both delicate canvases and heavy-duty power tools, tell the story of his life. Raised in Sacramento by a mechanic father and a bookkeeper mother, Todd inherited a unique blend of practical skill and meticulous detail. He spent his youth sketching in notebooks while helping his dad rebuild engines, a duality that defined his path. Drawn to the vibrant, rebellious art scene of the 1990s, he moved to San Francisco at 21 and never looked back.\n\nHe enrolled at City College of San Francisco, pursuing a Fine Art associate's degree. While he loved the theory, he felt more at home in the woodshop than in front of a blank canvas. A turning point came during an internship at a small SoMa gallery where he was asked to help install a complex sculpture. The challenge of problem-solving\u2014calculating weight loads, building custom mounts, and perfectly lighting the piece\u2014was a revelation. He found his true calling not in creating the art itself, but in giving it a physical home.\n\nThis discovery launched his career. Todd worked his way up from a freelance art handler to positions at several galleries before landing his current role as Head Preparator for a major museum. He is the respected, unflappable anchor of the exhibitions team, the one who ensures a priceless masterpiece is hung securely and safely.\n\nToday, Todd lives in a rent-controlled apartment in the Lower Haight. His daily routine is a ritual: a strong coffee from a local cafe, followed by a 2.8-mile bike commute, a path he knows by every pothole and mural. His social life revolves around a tight-knit group of fellow art-world lifers\u2014curators, technicians, and struggling artists\u2014who meet for beers at a beloved dive bar. A long-term relationship ended five years ago, largely because his partner wanted to leave the expensive, demanding city, but Todd couldn't imagine being anywhere else. San Francisco is woven into his identity. His dream isn't fame or fortune, but the quiet satisfaction of his craft and, maybe one day, owning a small condo. He hopes to mentor the next generation of preparators, passing on the knowledge held in his capable, steady hands."
